E. COLI EHEC - USA (04): (HAWAII), O157, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
****************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Thu 28 Mar 2013
Source: Pacific Business News [edited]
http://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/news/2013/03/28/hawaii-health-inspectors-search-for.html


Hawaii health investigators are looking at the restaurants, grocery stores and other places where 9 people who were sickened by _E. coli_ [O157] bacteria had bought and consumed food in an effort to track down the source of the contamination.

The sources of _E. coli_ could be any type of food, said Janice Okubo, a Department of Health spokeswoman. And right now, the state is reviewing records to see where all of the people dined out and bought their food. "We still have not found a common source," she said.

The 1st cases started appearing in February 2013, and 3 of the victims suffered from hemolytic uremic syndrome, which is a life-threatening complication of the infection, Okubo said. The 9 infected people include 6 children under age 10, and 4 of those children were hospitalized, Okubo said. One child is still in the hospital.

All of the cases are on Oahu, and this is a specific strain that isn't on the Mainland, Okubo said. "It's an unusual strain; we don't see it too often."

The health department also sent out an alert to physicians statewide last week for them to be on the lookout for symptoms in their patients. According to KITV, one person affected by the latest outbreak was a visitor. KITV reports that a total of 10 cases of the infection were reported statewide in 2012.

[Byline: Mark Abramson]

